{"timestamp": "2025-12-04 16:54:11.462720", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Based on the diagnosis report: Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\\n\\nSummary\\n- Detected anomaly: DNS name resolution is broken end-to-end. The DNS server at 10.200.0.2 (dns_server) is not answering queries (both UDP and TCP) from itself or from other nodes. This prevents resolution of local hostnames (e.g., web0.local, web99.local). \\n- Network layer health: Layer-3 reachability across all subnets and to the server farm is normal. HTTP services are reachable by IP. OSPF on the server_access_router appears to be advertising/learning routes as expected.\\n\\nKey Findings and Evidence\\n\\n1) End-to-end reachability is healthy\\n- Comprehensive inter-host pings succeeded with 0% loss and low RTTs across multiple subnets (10.<core>.<dist>.0/24). This indicates routing and basic connectivity are intact.\\n- Direct ICMP from hosts to server farm IPs works (e.g., host_1_1_1_1 to 10.200.0.2, 10.200.0.7, 10.200.0.3 all 0% loss).\\n- On server_access_router:\\n  - ip route shows 10.200.0.0/24 on br0, OSPF-learned routes to access subnets via eth7, and correct connected/link routes. This supports a healthy control plane.\\n\\n2) HTTP services are available by IP\\n- Curl to the load balancer IP (http://10.200.0.7) from hosts succeeds consistently (starttransfer around 0.27–0.33 s, total ~1.1 s).\\n- Curl to web server IP (http://10.200.0.3) from host is also successful (starttransfer ~0.19–0.35 s, total ~1.0–1.16 s).\\n- On the load_balancer host, Nginx is listening on 0.0.0.0:80. This confirms the application layer for web is fine when accessed via IP.\\n\\n3) DNS resolution is failing\\n- Curl to hostnames (web99.local, web0.local) from hosts stalls for ~5 seconds and returns no progress metrics (namelookup/connect/pretransfer/starttransfer all 0, total ~5.0 s), consistent with DNS lookup timeout.\\n- Dig to the DNS server times out from multiple vantage points:\\n  - From dns_server itself: dig @127.0.0.1 web99.local A and dig +tcp both time out.\\n  - From load_balancer and web_server_0: dig @10.200.0.2 web{0,99}.local also time out.\\n- Despite timeouts, the DNS daemon appears to be running:\\n  - named service is active (running); rndc status reports BIND operational with zones loaded (2 zones).\\n  - Sockets appear open: UDP “UNCONN” on 10.200.0.2:53 and 127.0.0.1:53; TCP LISTEN on both 127.0.0.1:53 and 10.200.0.2:53.\\n  - The zone file /etc/bind/db.local defines A records for web0–web3, web99, and ns1, and named.conf has:\\n    - listen-on port 53 { any; }; allow-query { any; }; recursion no;\\n    - zone \"local\" IN { type master; file \"/etc/bind/db.local\"; }\\n- There are no useful logs in journalctl for named. iptables-save showed only NAT table entries (Docker-related DNAT/SNAT for 127.0.0.11), and no clear filter rules were visible via iptables-save output.\\n\\nFault Localization\\n- Faulty node: dns_server (10.200.0.2).\\n- Scope: DNS service path on the dns_server host. The issue is local to the DNS server and not a routing/OSPF problem since ICMP and HTTP by IP are normal across the network and within the server VLAN.\\n\\nProbable Root Cause\\n- The BIND service (named) is running and listening, but DNS queries to both localhost and the server’s IP do not receive responses, indicating the application is not servicing queries. Most likely causes given the symptoms:\\n  - Host-based firewall/NFT rules on dns_server silently dropping inbound and/or outbound port 53 traffic (both UDP and TCP), including loopback. The iptables-save output does not show filter rules; nftables (inet filter) rules not displayed by iptables-save could be enforcing drops.\\n  - Less likely: a misconfiguration or conflicting options causing named to ignore/respond abnormally to queries; however, such misconfigurations usually yield RCODEs (REFUSED/SERVFAIL), not timeouts, and timeouts even to 127.0.0.1 strongly suggest packet filtering.\\n\\nImpact\\n- Hosts cannot resolve local service names (web0.local, web99.local), so application access by hostname fails or stalls.\\n- Direct IP access to services remains functional, so underlying network and servers are healthy.\\n\\nAdditional Observations\\n- The load_balancer host reports addresses “10.200.0.7 20.200.0.1”. This extra address does not appear to impact current issues but is noted for completeness.\\n\\nConclusion\\n- Anomaly confirmed: DNS service is unresponsive.\\n- Localization: dns_server host, DNS process path.\\n- Root cause: DNS server not returning responses, most consistent with local firewall/NFT filtering of port 53 traffic (including loopback), or equivalent host-level blocking, given named is running/listening and the zone is configured., please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='c95c93dc-574c-4d18-b15c-df624ef49f4e'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
